# /list-tasks — fetch open tasks from {{TASK_MANAGER}}

This skill is generated by `/process-setup` and lives at `.claude/skills/list-tasks/SKILL.md` in the consumer repo. It is invoked by the `/process` clarification skill via the Skill tool to populate the task picker.

The configured task manager for this repo is **{{TASK_MANAGER}}** (slug: `{{TASK_MANAGER_SLUG}}`).

- **Integration method:** `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}` — one of `mcp`, `cli`, `plugin`, or `api`.
- **Invocation:** `{{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}}` — the concrete tool / command / endpoint the user configured.
- **Scope (project / team / workspace):** `{{SCOPE}}` — the identifier and any filter/parameter name needed to narrow tasks to this repo's project.

## Output contract

Return a list of tasks, one per line, in this exact format so the caller can parse it:

```
<id>\t<title>\t<one-line description>
```

Tab-separated. Up to 20 tasks. Sorted by priority (highest first) if the source supports it; otherwise by recency.

If there are no open tasks, print a single line:

```
(no open tasks)
```

If credentials/config are missing or the call fails, print to stderr a one-line error starting with `LIST_TASKS_ERROR:` and exit non-zero. The caller will fall back to asking the user to describe a task manually.

The `id` you emit becomes `task_source = "{{TASK_MANAGER_SLUG}}:<id>"` — never let it contain whitespace, tabs, or shell metacharacters.

## How to fetch — follow the block matching `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}`

### If `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}` = `mcp`

Call the configured MCP tool (`{{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}}`) with arguments that scope to `{{SCOPE}}` and filter to open / not-done tasks. Map the response to the `<id>\t<title>\t<description>` contract: pick the most stable identifier the tool returns (issue key, number, or page id), the title field, and a description trimmed to ~120 chars with newlines replaced by spaces.

If the MCP tool is not available in the current session, print `LIST_TASKS_ERROR: mcp tool {{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}} not available` to stderr and exit 1.

### If `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}` = `cli`

Run the configured command (`{{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}}`) via Bash, scoped to `{{SCOPE}}` (add the documented filter/parameter from the scope field if the command doesn't already include it). Pipe the JSON output through `jq` to produce tab-separated rows in the contract format. Cap descriptions at 120 chars and strip newlines/tabs.

If the CLI exits non-zero or auth fails, print `LIST_TASKS_ERROR: <cli> failed: <stderr first line>` and exit 1.

### If `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}` = `plugin`

Invoke the configured slash command or skill (`{{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}}`) via the Skill tool, passing `{{SCOPE}}` as the scope argument if the plugin accepts one. The plugin is expected to return tasks in any structured form; reformat them into `<id>\t<title>\t<description>` lines before printing.

If the plugin is not registered in this session, print `LIST_TASKS_ERROR: plugin {{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}} not available` and exit 1.

### If `{{INTEGRATION_METHOD}}` = `api`

Make an HTTP request to the endpoint described in `{{INTEGRATION_INVOCATION}}`, using the auth env var(s) named there. Filter the response to open / not-done tasks scoped to `{{SCOPE}}`, then emit `<id>\t<title>\t<description>` rows (description trimmed to ~120 chars, newlines/tabs stripped).

If any required env var is unset, print `LIST_TASKS_ERROR: <var name> not set` and exit 1. If the HTTP call fails, print `LIST_TASKS_ERROR: <endpoint> returned <status>` and exit 1.

## Notes for the caller

- Each emitted line is `<id>\t<title>\t<description>`. Split on the first two tabs only — descriptions may contain spaces (but never newlines or tabs).
- The `id` is opaque to the /process skill except for the `{{TASK_MANAGER_SLUG}}:` prefix it adds.
- If you change the task manager, integration method, or scope, re-run `/process-setup` and pick again. This file will be regenerated.
